\b Troubleshooting\par
\par
Wheel doesn't work in the game, but it works inside x360ce Application.\par
\b0 Some games will only operate when the controller is considered to be the gamepad, even if it is the steering wheel. Try to:\par
\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 1.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent0\pnstart1\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\fi-360\li720     Run x360ce.exe\par
{\pntext\f0 2.\tab}    Select tab with your Wheel Controller.\par
{\pntext\f0 3.\tab}    Open [Advanced] tab page.\par
{\pntext\f0 4.\tab}    Set "Device Type" drop down list value to: GamePad\par
{\pntext\f0 5.\tab}    Click [Save] button.\par
{\pntext\f0 6.\tab}    Close x360ce Application, run game.\par
\pard\par
\b How to reduce wheel dead zone (GTA, Mafia II, ...)?\par
\b0\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 1.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent0\pnstart1\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\fi-360\li720     Run x360ce.exe\par
{\pntext\f0 2.\tab}    Select tab with your Wheel Controller.\par
{\pntext\f0 3.\tab}    Open [Advanced] tab page.\par
{\pntext\f0 4.\tab}    Select "Enabled (XInput, 80%)" from "AntiDeadZone" drop down in order to reduce dead zone by 80%.\par
{\pntext\f0 5.\tab}    Click [Save] button.\par
{\pntext\f0 6.\tab}    Close x360ce Application, run game.\par
\pard\par
    Note: Some games have control issues when the dead zone is reduced by 100%. \par
\par
\b Do I need to run x360ce Application during the game?\par
\b0 No, You do not need. Close x360ce during the game, because the game does not need it, and the application uses computer resources. The application is just a GUI for editing the x360ce.ini and test controller.\par
\par
\b Warning - Configuration file version does not match x360ce version.\par
\b0 This occurs because the current version of the application is not completely compatible with the DLL just yet.\par
You can resolve this by adding Version=1 under the [Options] section in x360ce.ini\par
\par
\b Controller tab won't turn green / Red light on Controller 1,2 etc.\par
\b0 This can occur for a number of reasons.\par
\par
\pard{\pntext\f0 1.\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pnf0\pnindent0\pnstart1\pndec{\pntxta.}}
\fi-360\li720     The configuration utility DOES NOT work with the 64bit version of x360ce, it will only work with the 32bit version. This is the case regardless of whether your windows is 32bit or 64bit.\par
{\pntext\f0 2.\tab}    The DInput state of the control might be incorrect due to previous application crashing and not unloading the control or some other reason. Opening up Joy.cpl (Set Up Usb Game Controllers) and clicking the Advanced button, and then Okaying out of the window that appears can fix it.\par
{\pntext\f0 3.\tab}    The controller profile loaded may match the name of the control but not actually be for the controller you own - in this case you might see button numbers or axes mapped that do not appear in the joy.cpl test page.\par
{\pntext\f0 4.\tab}    The controller profile might have PassThrough set. A growing number of profiles have been uploaded that do this, i have no idea why as it disables x360ce and just bloats the list of available profiles.\par
{\pntext\f0 5.\tab}    There just might not be a profile for your control at all - The light should turn green once atleast the 2 sticks, triggers and Dpad are assigned. Sometimes the application needs to be restarted after assigning these for the light to turn green.\par
